<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_ring_homo" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Ring homomorphisms and ideals</title>
<subsection xml:id="ss_rings">
<title>Ring homomorphisms</title>


    <definition xml:id="d_ring_homo">
    <title>Ring homomorphism</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> be rings. A <term>ring homomorphism</term> is a function <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> satisfying the following properties. 
    <ol marker="(i)">
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\phi(r+r')=\phi(r)+\phi(r')</m> (<ie/>, <m>\phi</m> is a group homomorphism from <m>(R,+)</m> to <m>(S,+)</m>).
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\phi(r\, r')=\phi(r)\phi(r')</m> for all <m>r,r'\in R</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\phi(1_R)=1_S</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    Given a ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m>, its <term>kernel</term> <m>\ker \phi</m> is defined as 
    <md>
       <mrow>  \ker\phi\amp =\{r\in R\mid \phi(r)=0\}\amp </mrow>
    </md>.
    An <term>isomorphism</term> is a bijective ring homomorphism. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Given rings <m>R</m> and <m>S</m>, we will write <m>\Hom(R,S)</m> for the set of all ring homomorphisms from <m>R</m> to <m>S</m>: <ie/>, 
        <md>
            <mrow>\Hom(R,S)\amp =\{\phi\colon R\rightarrow S\mid \phi \text{ a ring homomorphism}\} \amp </mrow>
        </md>.
        
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <warning>
        <title>Ring homomorphism</title>
        <p>
            The Dummit and Foote text does not include axiom (iii), since rings there are not assumed to be unital. Additionally, (iii) does not follow logically form (i) and (ii): <eg/>, the zero map between any two rings satisfies (i) and (ii), but not (iii) necessarily. 
        </p>
    </warning>
    <proposition xml:id="prop_ring_homos">
        <title>Ring homomorphisms</title>
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Subring inclusions are ring homomorphisms. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The composition of ring homomorphisms is a ring homomorphism. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Given a bijective ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m>, its inverse <m>\phi^{-1}\colon S\rightarrow R</m> is a ring homomorphism. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> is a ring homomorphism, then <m>\phi(R)</m> is a subring of <m>S</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> is injective if and only if <m>\ker \phi =\{0\}</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Left to the reader.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <remark>
        <title>Group structure of rings</title>
        
        <p>
            The last statement of <xref ref="prop_ring_homos"/> follows immediately from the fact that a ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> is in particular a group homomorphism with respect to the additive structures of <m>R</m> and <m>S</m>. This is one of many examples where we will exploit the group structure of rings to obtain useful results (or steps toward a result) in the context of rings. 
        </p>
    </remark>
    
    <example xml:id="eg_empty_ring_homo_set">
    <title><m>\Hom(\Z/3\Z, \Z/2\Z)</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Prove that <m>\Hom(\Z/3\Z, \Z/2\Z)=\emptyset</m>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    Assume by contradiction that <m>\phi\colon \Z/3\Z\rightarrow \Z/2\Z</m> is a ring homomorphism. Since in particular <m>\phi</m> is a group homomorphism, <m>\phi([1]_3)</m> is an element of <m>\Z/2\Z</m> of order dividing <m>3</m>. (See <xref ref="prop_homs_cyclic"/>.) But <m>[0]_2</m> is the only such element. Thus <m>\phi([1]_3)=[0]_2</m>: a contradiction, since <m>[0]_2\ne 1</m> in <m>\Z/2\Z</m>. 
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
    
    
    <activity xml:id="spec_hom_Z">
    <title>Ring homomorphisms from <m>\Z</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a ring. There is a unique ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon \Z\rightarrow R</m>, defined as <m>\phi(n)=n\cdot 1_R</m> for all <m>n\in \Z</m>. In particular, <m>\Hom(\Z,R)=\{\phi\}</m> is a singleton. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    <activity xml:id="spec_poly_ring_homo">
    <title>Polynomial ring homomorphisms</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> be commutative rings. A ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R[x]\rightarrow S</m> is uniquely determined by its restriction <m>\phi_R</m> to the subring <m>R\subseteq R[x]</m> and the value <m>\phi(x)\in S</m>. Conversely, given a ring homomorphism <m>\psi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> and an element <m>s\in S</m>, there is a unique ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R[x]\rightarrow S</m> such that <m>\phi_R=\psi</m> and <m>\phi(x)=s</m>. Thus we have the following bijection:
    </p>
    <image xml:id="im_poly_ring_homo" width="75%">
                <shortdescription>Description of polynomial ring homomorphisms</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                \Hom(R[x],S) \arrow[r,leftrightarrow] \amp \Hom(R,S)\times S \\
                \phi \arrow[r,mapsto] \amp (\phi\vert_R, \phi(x)) \\
                \phi(\sum_{k=0}^na_kx^k)=\sum_{k=0}^n \psi(a_k)s^k \amp (\psi, s) \arrow[l,mapsto]
                \end{tikzcd}
                </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
        Given a ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R[x]\rightarrow S</m> corresponding to the pair <m>(\psi, s)\in \Hom(R,S)\times S</m>, if the map <m>\psi</m> is clear from the context, we will often call <m>\phi</m> the <term>evaluation at <m>s</m></term> homomorphism.
    </p>
    <p>
        Similarly, if <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> are nontrivial commutative rings, and if <m>\psi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> is a ring homomorphism, identifying <m>\psi</m> with the map <m>R\rightarrow S[x]</m> obtained by composing with the subring inclusion <m>S\subseteq S[x]</m>, we will often use <m>\phi</m> (or its name) to refer to the corresponding ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R[x]\rightarrow S[x]</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </activity>
    <example xml:id="eg_poly_homo">
    <title><m>\Hom(\Z[x],R)</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring. Show that there is a bijection between <m>\Hom(\Z[x], R)</m> and <m>R</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    From <xref ref="spec_poly_ring_homo"/> we know there is a bijection between 
    <m>\Hom(\Z[x], R)</m> and <m>\Hom(\Z, R)\times R</m>. From <xref ref="spec_hom_Z"/>, on the other hand, we know that <m>\Hom(\Z, R)=\{\phi}</m>, where <m>\phi(n)=n\cdot 1_R=n\in R</m> for all <m>n\in \Z</m>. The result follows since <m>\{\phi\}\times R</m> is in bijective correspondence with <m>R</m>. More explicitly, all homomorphisms <m>\phi\colon \Z[x]\rightarrow R</m> are of the form 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow>\phi(\sum_{k=0}^na_kx^k) \amp = \sum_{k=0}^na_k r^k</mrow>
    </md>,
    for some <m>r\in R</m>. Note that the integers <m>a_k</m> appearing on the right must be interpreted as the ring elements 
    <md>
        <mrow>a_k \amp =a_k\cdot 1_R\in R</mrow>
    </md>.
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
    
    <activity xml:id="spec_augementation_map">
    <title>Augmentation map</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nontrivial commutative ring, and let <m>G</m> be a finite group The map <m>\phi\colon R\, G\rightarrow R</m> defined as 
    <md>
        <mrow>\phi(\sum_{g\in G}a_g g)\amp = \sum_{g\in G} a_g \amp </mrow>
    </md>
    is a surjective ring homomorphism called the <term>augmentation map</term>. Its kernel 
    <md>
        <mrow>\ker \phi \amp =\{\sum_{g\in G}a_g\, g\in R\, G\mid \sum_{g\in G}a_g=0\}</mrow>
    </md>
    is called the <term>augmentation ideal</term>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </activity>
    <example xml:id="eg_augmentation_map">
    <title>Augmentation map</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nontrivial commutative ring, and let <m>G</m> be a finite group. Prove that the augmentation map <m>\phi\colon R\, G\rightarrow R</m> is a surjective ring homomorphism. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    It is easy to see that <m>\phi</m> is group homomorphism, <m>\phi(1)=1_R</m>, and moreover that it is surjective (since <m>\phi(r\, e)=r</m> for any <m>r\in R</m>). It remains only to show that it is multiplicative. Given elements <m>r=\sum_{g\in G}a_g\, g</m>, <m>s=\sum_{g\in G}b_g\, g</m> of <m>R\, G</m>, we have <m>rs=\sum_{g\in G}c_g\, g</m>, where
    <md>
        <mrow>c_g \amp =\sum_{\substack{(h,k)\in G\times G\\ hk=g}}a_h b_k</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \sum_{h\in G}a_h b_{h^{-1}g}</mrow>
    </md>.
    Thus 
    <md>
        <mrow>\phi(rs) \amp =\sum_{g\in G}c_g</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =\sum_{g\in G}\sum_{h\in G}a_hb_{h^{-1}g}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =\sum_{h\in H}\sum_{g\in G}a_hb_{h^{-1}g} \amp (+ \text{ is comm. and assoc.})</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =\sum_{h\in G}a_h\sum_{g\in G}b_{h^{-1}g} \amp (\text{dist.})</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \sum_{h\in G}a_h\sum_{g'\in G}b_{g'}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \sum_{g\in G}a_h \cdot \sum_{g\in G}b_g \amp (\text{dist.})</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \phi(r)\phi(s)</mrow>
    </md>,
    as desired. 
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>


    
</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="ss_ideals">
<title>Ideals</title>
<definition xml:id="d_ideal">
<title>Ideal</title>
<statement>
<p>
An <term>ideal</term> of a ring <m>R</m> is a subset <m>I\subseteq R</m> satisfying the following properties. 
<ol marker="(i)">
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>I</m> is a subgroup of  <m>(R,+)</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>I</m> is <term>closed under left multiplication</term>: <ie/>, if <m>i\in I</m>, then <m>ri\in I</m> for all <m>r\in R</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>I</m> is <term>closed under right multiplication</term>: <ie/>, if <m>i\in I</m>, then <m>ir\in I</m> for all <m>r\in R</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
A subset <m>I</m> of <m>R</m> is a <term>left ideal</term> if it satisfies (i) and (ii); it is a <term>right ideal</term> if it satisfies (i) and (iii). 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<example xml:id="eg_trivial_ideals">
<title>Trivial ideals</title>
<statement>
<p>
Given a ring <m>R</m>, the sets <m>\{0\}</m> and <m>R</m> are easily seen to be ideals of <m>R</m>. We will call these <term>trivial ideals</term>. Additionally we will call an ideal <m>I</m> <term>nonzero</term> if <m>I\ne \{0\}</m>, and <term>proper</term> if <m>I\ne R</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>

</p>
</solution>
</example>

<proposition xml:id="prop_ideals">
<title>Ideals</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>R</m> be a ring. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>(I_\alpha)_{\alpha\in J}</m> is an indexed family of ideals of <m>R</m>, then <m>\bigcap_{\alpha\in J}I_\alpha</m> is an ideal. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>I</m> and <m>J</m> are ideals of <m>R</m>, then so is <m>I+J</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The set <m>IJ</m> defined as the set of all finite sums of products <m>ij</m>, where <m>i\in I</m> and <m>j\in J</m>, is an ideal of <m>R</m>. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For a positive integer <m>n</m>, we define <m>I^n</m> to be the <m>n</m>-fold ideal product of <m>I</m> with itself. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> is a ring homomorphism, then <m>\ker\phi</m> is an ideal of <m>R</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            We leave all but (3) to the reader. For (3), it is clear that <m>IJ</m> as defined is a subgroup of <m>(R,+)</m>. Given any <m>r,s\in R</m>, and element <m>a=\sum_{k=1}^ni_kj_k\in IJ</m>, with <m>i_k\in I</m> and <m>j_k\in J</m> for all <m>k</m>, we have 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>ras \amp = \sum_{k=1}^n(ri_k)(j_ks)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \sum_{k=1}^ni_k' j_k'</mrow>
            </md>,
            where 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>i_k' \amp = ri_k\in I \amp (I \text{ an ideal})</mrow>
                <mrow>j_k' \amp j_ks\in J \amp (J \text{ an idea})</mrow>
            </md>,
            showing that <m>ras\in IJ</m>, as desired. 
        </p>
    </proof>
</proposition>
<definition xml:id="d_gen_ideal">
<title>Generated ideals</title>
<notation>
    <usage><m>(A)</m></usage>
  <description>the ideal generated by <m>A</m></description>
</notation>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>A</m> be a subset of a ring <m>R</m>. The <term>ideal generated by <m>A</m></term>, denoted <m>(A)</m>, is the intersection of all ideals of <m>R</m> containing <m>A</m>: <ie/>,
<md>
    <mrow> (A)  \amp = \bigcap_{\substack{I \text{ ideal} \\ A\subseteq I}} I </mrow>
</md>.
If <m>A=\{a_1,a_2,\dots, a_n\}</m>, we wite <m>(A)=(a_1,a_2,\dots, a_n)</m> for <m>A</m>; similarly, if <m>A=(a_1,a_2,\dots, )</m>, we write <m>(A)=(a_1,a_2,\dots)</m>.
</p>
<p>
    An ideal <m>I</m> is <term>finitely generated</term> if we have <m>I=(a_1,a_2,\dots, a_n)</m> for some elements <m>a_i\in R</m>; it is <term>principal</term> if <m>I=(a)</m> for some <m>a\in R</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<proposition xml:id="prop_generated_ideals">
<title>Generated ideals</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>A</m> be a subset of the ring <m>R</m>. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>(A)</m> is the smallest ideal of <m>R</m> containing <m>A</m> in the following sense: if <m>I</m> is an ideal of <m>R</m> containing <m>A</m>, then <m>(A)\subseteq I</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>(A)</m> is the set of all finite sums of elements of the form <m>r a s</m>, where <m>r,s\in R</m> and <m>a\in A</m>: <ie/>, letting <m>T=\{ras\mid a\in A, r,s\in R\}</m>, we have <m>(A)=\angvec{T}</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</proposition>
<corollary xml:id="cor_gen_ideal_kernel">
    <title>Generated ideals and kernels</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> be a ring homomorphism. For any set <m>A\subseteq R</m>, we have <m>(A)\subseteq \ker\phi</m> if and only if <m>\phi(a)=0</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>. 
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Since <m>\ker\phi</m> is an ideal of <m>R</m>,  we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>(A)\subseteq \ker\phi \amp  \iff A\subseteq \ker\phi \amp (<xref ref="prop_generated_ideals" text="global"/>)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp \iff \phi(a)=0 \text{ for all } a\in A</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </proof>
</corollary>

<example xml:id="eg_ideals_integers">
<title>Ideals of <m>\Z</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Give an explicit description of the set of all ideals of <m>\Z</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
Let <m>I</m> be an ideal of <m>\Z</m>. Since in particular <m>I</m> is a subgroup of <m>\Z</m>, we know that <m>I</m> can be written uniquely as 
<md>
    <mrow>I \amp =\angvec{n}</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp =\{kn\mid k\in \Z\}</mrow>
</md> 
for some nonnegative integer <m>n\in \Z_{\geq 0}</m>. It is easy to see, using <xref ref="prop_generated_ideals"/>, that <m>\angvec{n}=(n)</m>, the principal ideal generated by <m>(n)</m>. We conclude that the correspondence 
<md>
    <mrow>n \amp \leftrightarrow (n)</mrow>
</md>
gives a bijective correspondence between nonnegative integers of <m>\Z</m> and ideals of <m>\Z</m>. In particular, all ideals of <m>\Z</m> are principal. 
</p>
</solution>
</example>
<p>
    Recall that for any ring <m>R</m>, there is a unique ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon \Z\rightarrow R</m>: namely, <m>\phi(n)=n\cdot 1_R</m> for all <m>n\in R</m>. We can define the <term>characteristic</term> of a ring using this homomorphism. 
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_characteristic_ring">
    <title>Characteristic of a ring</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>\char R</m></usage>
      <description>characteristic of the ring <m>R</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero ring. The <term>characteristic</term> of <m>R</m>, denoted <m>\char R</m>, is defined as the nonnegative integer <m>n</m> such that <m>\ker \phi = (n)</m>, where <m>\phi\colon \Z\rightarrow R</m> is the unique ring homomorphism from <m>\Z</m> to <m>R</m>. Equivalently, <m>\char R</m> is either the smallest positive integeger <m>n</m> satisfying <m>n\cdot 1_R=0</m>, or 0 if no such integer exists. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
<example xml:id="eg_ideals_division_rings">
<title>Ideals of division rings</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>D</m> be a division ring. Prove that the only ideals of <m>D</m> are <m>\{0\}</m> and <m>D</m> itself. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
Let <m>I</m> be an ideal of <m>D</m> that is not the zero ideal, and let <m>a\in I</m> be any nonzero element. Since <m>D</m> is a division ring, there is an element <m>b\in D</m> satisfying <m>ab=ba=1</m>. It follows that for any <m>r\in D</m>, we have 
<md>
    <mrow>r \amp =r\cdot 1= r(ba)=(rb)a\in I</mrow>
</md>,
and thus that <m>I=D</m>. 
</p>
</solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="eg_ideals_matrix_rings">
<title>Ideals of <m>M_n(R)</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be commutative ring. Prove that all ideals of <m>M_n(R)</m> are of the form <m>M_n(I)</m> for some ideal <m>I\subseteq R</m>, where we define 
<md>
    <mrow>M_n(I) \amp = \{[a_{ij}]\in M_n(R)\mid a_{ij}\in I\}</mrow>
</md>.
In particular, given a field <m>K</m>, the only ideals of <m>M_n(K)</m> are <m>\{0\}</m> and <m>M_n(K)</m> itself. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
Left as homework exercise. 
</p>
</solution>
</example>
<definition xml:id="d_simple">
<title>Simple ring</title>
<statement>
<p>
A nonzero ring <m>R</m> is <term>simple</term> if its only ideals are <m>\{0\}</m> and <m>R</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<p>
    From the previous examples, we see that fields, division rings more generally, and also matrix rings over fields are all examples of simple rings. One useful property of simple rings is that any nontrivial homomorphism out of a simple ring is injective. 
</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop_simple_ring_homo">
    <title>Homomorphisms from simple rings</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>R</m> be a simple ring. If <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> is a ring homomorphism with <m>S</m> a nonzero ring, then <m>\phi</m> is injective. 
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Since <m>S</m> is nonzero, the ideal <m>\ker\phi</m> is not equal to <m>R</m>. It follows that <m>\ker\phi=(0)</m>, and hence that <m>\phi</m> is injective (by group homomorphism properties). 
        </p>
    </proof>
</proposition>
<p>
    We end this section with an official definition of a ring algebra. 
</p>

<definition xml:id="d_algebra">
<title><m>R</m>-algebra</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring. An <term><m>R</m>-algebra</term> (or <term>algebra over <m>R</m></term>) is a nonzero ring <m>S</m> together with a ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> such that <m>\im\phi=\phi(R)</m> is contained in the center of <m>S</m> (<ie/>, elements of the subring <m>\phi(R)\subseteq S</m> commute with all elements of <m>S</m>). We write <m>S/R</m> to denote that <m>S</m> is an <m>R</m>-algebra. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<p>
    It is easy to see that our constructions <m>R\, G</m>, <m>M_n(R)</m>, <m>R[x]</m>, and <m>R[[x]]</m> are all examples of <m>R</m>-algebras. Furthermore,  in these examples, the corresponding ring homomorphism defining the <m>R</m>-algebra structure is injective, allowing us to identify <m>R</m> as a subring of the given <m>R</m>-algebra. This of course is not always the case, simply because a ring homomorphism need not be injective. However, it is always the case with algebras <m>S/F</m> where <m>F</m> is a field. This is because nontrivial ring homomorphisms <m>\phi\colon F\rightarrow S</m> are injective by <xref ref="prop_simple_ring_homo"/>
</p>


</subsection>
</section>